WEBVTT

00:04.308 --> 00:06.963
<i>- Apologies I couldn't scrub
in last night.</i>

00:07.007 --> 00:09.052
- If you want to shadow me,
consider yourself on call.

00:09.096 --> 00:11.489
I don't like having
my time wasted.

00:11.533 --> 00:14.318
<i>- The hospital will
discontinue the Vas-COM</i>

00:14.362 --> 00:17.104
until it can be proven
to be safe.

00:17.147 --> 00:19.802
- Hold off on banning
the Vas-COM just yet.

00:19.845 --> 00:22.370
Given my son-in-law
is a consultant for Vasik,

00:22.413 --> 00:25.590
I shouldn't be the one
to deliver this news.

00:25.634 --> 00:28.332
- It's time to do
our random drug testing.

00:28.376 --> 00:30.247
- I'm not gonna pass this test.

00:30.291 --> 00:31.727
- Here.
- What's this?

00:31.770 --> 00:34.469
- It'll make the last traces
of the drug undetectable.

00:34.512 --> 00:36.558
- My niece, Holly,
is singing carols.

00:36.601 --> 00:38.081
I thought you'd want
to come with me.

00:38.125 --> 00:41.084
- Yeah.
Let's go cheer Holly on.

00:42.564 --> 00:48.352
all: Six, five, four,
three, two, one!

00:48.396 --> 00:51.399
[cheering]

00:51.442 --> 00:53.270
choir:
♪ Dashing through the snow

00:53.314 --> 00:55.316
♪ In a one-horse open sleigh

00:55.359 --> 00:57.361
- That's my niece.

00:57.405 --> 00:59.450
choir: ♪ Laughing all the way,
ha ha ha ♪

00:59.494 --> 01:03.150
♪ Bells on bobtails ring,
making spirits bright ♪

01:03.193 --> 01:05.195
♪ What fun it is
to ride and sing ♪

01:05.239 --> 01:06.892
♪ A sleighing song tonight

01:06.936 --> 01:10.374
- After this,
will you be my guinea pig?

01:10.418 --> 01:14.117
I'm testing out a new eggnog
recipe for the family party,

01:14.161 --> 01:16.467
and my place is just
a couple blocks from here.

01:16.511 --> 01:18.687
choir: ♪ Jingle bells,
jingle all the way ♪

01:18.730 --> 01:20.819
- Sure.
- Okay.

01:20.863 --> 01:26.260
choir: ♪ In a one-horse
open sleigh ♪

01:26.303 --> 01:28.697
♪ Jingle all the way, hey!

01:28.740 --> 01:30.307
- Oh, thank you.

01:35.182 --> 01:39.142
Vanessa,
your drug test results.

01:39.186 --> 01:42.145
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

01:42.189 --> 01:45.496
<i>♪</i>

01:45.540 --> 01:46.628
- Negative.

01:47.672 --> 01:48.891
- Thank God.

01:48.934 --> 01:50.153
- Thank you, Maggie.

01:50.197 --> 01:52.460
<i>[sentimental music]</i>

01:52.503 --> 01:54.201
Thank you.

01:54.244 --> 02:01.121
<i>♪</i>

02:03.732 --> 02:05.821
- I feel like
a lot of this is my fault.

02:08.215 --> 02:10.826
I'm sorry for the stress
that I caused you.

02:10.869 --> 02:12.480
For coming into your life
the way that I did,

02:12.523 --> 02:13.785
for wanting you here,

02:13.829 --> 02:15.918
and just never
telling you the truth.

02:15.961 --> 02:18.747
- No, no.
I understand why you did it.

02:18.790 --> 02:20.879
You had--you had a daughter,
and you wanted to meet her.

02:20.923 --> 02:22.403
If ever--if I ever
were in your shoes,

02:22.446 --> 02:24.274
I probably would have done
the same thing.

02:26.537 --> 02:27.538
Okay?

02:32.326 --> 02:33.370
- Okay.

02:45.339 --> 02:47.689
- Okay, cheers.

02:47.732 --> 02:48.951
- Cheers.

02:53.521 --> 02:54.478
- Too much vanilla.

02:54.522 --> 02:56.698
- No. That's perfect.

02:56.741 --> 02:58.178
- We have a winner.

03:04.009 --> 03:07.970
You know,
with Dr. Cooper's situation,

03:08.013 --> 03:09.667
the company is concerned that

03:09.711 --> 03:12.801
they don't have anyone
advocating for the Vas-COM.

03:12.844 --> 03:14.846
And I'm sorry if this
is a little personal,

03:14.890 --> 03:18.415
but I understand that
you have financial worries.

03:19.808 --> 03:21.679
- It's no secret.

03:21.723 --> 03:24.508
- We can help you. Look...

03:25.857 --> 03:30.688
Will, I wouldn't mention
this if I didn't trust you.

03:30.732 --> 03:32.908
And I hope you feel
you can trust me.

03:34.344 --> 03:36.433
- I do, Jessa.

03:36.477 --> 03:38.479
- So here's the deal.

03:38.522 --> 03:40.263
Vasik can offer you
the same arrangement

03:40.307 --> 03:41.743
they had with Dr. Cooper.

03:43.701 --> 03:47.705
- Arrangement?
I don't understand.

03:47.749 --> 03:49.794
- For every Vas-COM catheter
the hospital ordered,

03:49.838 --> 03:51.970
Dr. Cooper
received a percentage.

03:52.014 --> 03:55.017
- Really? Wow.
- Yeah.

03:55.060 --> 03:58.542
I mean, these catheters are
used once, and then discarded.

03:58.586 --> 04:00.283
If we got enough departments
behind them,

04:00.327 --> 04:02.764
the hospital could go
through thousands.

04:04.418 --> 04:05.549
What do you think?

04:05.593 --> 04:07.899
- That sounds great. But...

04:07.943 --> 04:09.858
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

04:09.901 --> 04:12.426
I mean, isn't this kind
of like kickbacks?

04:13.688 --> 04:15.298
- You don't have to worry
about that.

04:15.342 --> 04:17.822
I mean, you're completely safe.

04:17.866 --> 04:20.303
- Okay, good.

04:20.347 --> 04:22.914
I mean, but Medicare.
I mean, insurance companies?

04:22.958 --> 04:25.439
They don't ever question
these charges?

04:25.482 --> 04:26.831
- You'd be surprised.

04:26.875 --> 04:30.008
I mean, Vas-COM catheter
is a small ticket item.

04:30.052 --> 04:31.401
<i>They hardly notice.</i>

04:31.445 --> 04:33.925
<i>And besides, even if someone
did question it,</i>

04:33.969 --> 04:36.711
<i>then the doctor could always
justify it clinically.</i>

04:36.754 --> 04:38.365
<i>I mean,
that's the beauty part.</i>

04:38.408 --> 04:40.802
<i>Look, you don't have
to give me an answer tonight,</i>

04:40.845 --> 04:42.891
<i>but let me just say I think</i>

04:42.934 --> 04:45.023
<i>you and I would be
a good team.</i>

04:46.982 --> 04:49.724
- Oh, my God.
This is a disaster.

04:49.767 --> 04:51.421
- We can go to the FBI now.

04:51.465 --> 04:52.944
- Yeah, there's no question
these are felonies.

04:52.988 --> 04:54.468
Why didn't you tell me
about this sooner?

04:54.511 --> 04:55.817
- I didn't have enough.

04:55.860 --> 04:57.993
And even when I tried
to get the Vas-COM pulled,

04:58.036 --> 04:59.342
the board refused.

04:59.386 --> 05:00.952
You were there.
- Yeah.

05:00.996 --> 05:04.086
- And Dr. Halstead put himself
in a very difficult position

05:04.129 --> 05:06.610
for months
in order to get that.

05:06.654 --> 05:08.786
- All right, look,
we can't blindside the board.

05:08.830 --> 05:10.962
Before we go to the FBI,
I've got to brief them.

05:11.006 --> 05:13.095
- Well, do it quickly, because
I'm not sitting on this.

05:13.138 --> 05:14.705
- Message received.

05:14.749 --> 05:15.706
But until you hear back
from me,

05:15.750 --> 05:16.838
it is business as usual.

05:16.881 --> 05:19.101
Please, not a word of this
to anyone.

05:19.144 --> 05:21.538
Dr. Halstead?
- All right.

05:21.582 --> 05:24.106
- Send me a copy
of that recording.

05:24.149 --> 05:26.413
This is a friggin' disaster.

05:26.456 --> 05:33.463
<i>♪</i>

05:40.731 --> 05:42.907
- Dr. Halstead?
- Lily.

05:42.951 --> 05:44.213
Lily, my baby, she's so sick.

05:44.256 --> 05:45.736
- Yeah, something's
really wrong with her.

05:45.780 --> 05:48.173
- You're going to Treatment 3.
- Okay. I'm Dr. Halstead.

05:48.217 --> 05:49.827
We're gonna take good care
of Lily.

05:49.871 --> 05:51.960
Find Dr. Scott.
- You got it.

05:53.701 --> 05:55.398
- They said the vomiting
started a few days ago.

05:55.442 --> 05:57.095
- We didn't think it was
anything serious.

05:57.139 --> 05:59.968
I mean, babies spit up, right?
But it just kept getting worse.

06:00.011 --> 06:01.796
- After she nursed,
she couldn't hold it down.

06:01.839 --> 06:03.972
- She's always been so active,
and now she's--

06:04.015 --> 06:05.930
- Listless?
- Yes.

06:05.974 --> 06:07.758
- How often have you been
changing her diaper

06:07.802 --> 06:09.281
because it's wet?

06:09.325 --> 06:12.154
- I'm not sure.
Two or three times a day. Why?

06:12.197 --> 06:14.939
- Less than six means
a baby's dehydrated.

06:14.983 --> 06:16.898
- So we'd like to get Lily
some fluids.

06:16.941 --> 06:18.639
- Mm-hmm.
- Okay.

06:18.682 --> 06:20.423
- 30 cc/kg bolus
of normal saline.

06:20.467 --> 06:21.642
- You got it.

06:21.685 --> 06:23.426
- And a maintenance rate
of 12 cc per hour.

06:23.470 --> 06:25.123
- Okay.

06:25.167 --> 06:26.777
- What's causing this?

06:26.821 --> 06:28.692
- Well, given her symptoms,
it could be a number of things,

06:28.736 --> 06:31.173
but I don't want to speculate
until we run some tests.

06:31.216 --> 06:33.436
- Maggie, CBC, CMP, and CRP.
- Right.

06:33.480 --> 06:36.004
- We'll be back when we get
some results in, okay?

06:42.097 --> 06:43.141
- Crockett?

06:43.185 --> 06:45.143
- Avery.
What are you doing here?

06:45.187 --> 06:47.189
- Stalking you.
- Uh-oh.

06:47.232 --> 06:49.147
- I had a follow-up
with my orthopedist.

06:49.191 --> 06:50.801
- Oh. Is everything good?
- Mm.

06:50.845 --> 06:52.237
Humpty Dumpty
is back together again.

06:52.281 --> 06:53.413
- Well, that's good.

06:53.456 --> 06:55.415
- Avery, stop bothering
Dr. Marcel.

06:55.458 --> 06:56.720
We have a patient to see.

06:56.764 --> 06:58.330
- Oh, no bother at all.
- Hi, Mom.

06:58.374 --> 07:00.115
It's good to see you too.

07:00.158 --> 07:02.378
- Mr. Carmona's in pre-op.
Dr. Marcel?

07:02.422 --> 07:03.945
- Yeah.

07:03.988 --> 07:06.730
- Bye, Dr. Marcel.
- Okay.

07:10.168 --> 07:11.735
- Happy day, Reuben.

07:13.215 --> 07:15.478
- I couldn't believe it
when I got the call.

07:15.522 --> 07:17.175
- We've been waiting
for months.

07:17.219 --> 07:18.481
- So long.

07:18.525 --> 07:20.178
- Reuben didn't make it easy
to find a liver.

07:20.222 --> 07:23.094
B negative.
It's a very rare blood type.

07:23.138 --> 07:24.400
- But we finally got a match,

07:24.444 --> 07:26.794
and its anatomy is excellent
for transplant.

07:26.837 --> 07:29.187
- We're so grateful.

07:29.231 --> 07:31.015
Best Christmas ever.

07:31.059 --> 07:32.843
<i>[sentimental music]</i>

07:32.887 --> 07:35.019
- Okay, Reuben, now you're
gonna take a nice long nap

07:35.063 --> 07:37.021
and wake up with a new liver.

07:37.065 --> 07:40.503
- I love you, Papi.
- Don't cry, mija.

07:40.547 --> 07:43.158
- Hey, you're gonna do great.

07:43.201 --> 07:45.029
- Sure am.

07:45.073 --> 07:51.514
<i>♪</i>

07:51.558 --> 07:54.212
- And shouldn't
have to have surgery.

07:54.256 --> 07:55.953
- We got Lily's
test results back.

07:55.997 --> 07:57.868
- We looking up her symptoms
on the internet, and it said

07:57.912 --> 08:00.088
that she might have something
called pyloric stenosis.

08:00.131 --> 08:01.872
- And she'll need surgery.
- No. No, no, no.

08:01.916 --> 08:04.135
She does not have
pyloric stenosis, okay?

08:04.179 --> 08:06.398
- No, her labs show
she's low in potassium.

08:06.442 --> 08:07.878
It's a mild
electrolyte imbalance.

08:07.922 --> 08:09.053
We're not sure yet,

08:09.097 --> 08:10.881
but it's most likely
a viral gastritis.

08:10.925 --> 08:13.144
- More commonly known
as a stomach flu.

08:13.188 --> 08:15.190
- That's all?
- We hope so.

08:15.233 --> 08:16.452
We're gonna keep Lily on fluids

08:16.496 --> 08:18.062
and monitor
her condition, okay?

08:18.106 --> 08:20.108
Best-case scenario,
it resolves on its own.

08:23.067 --> 08:24.112
- Thank you.
- All right.

08:24.155 --> 08:25.983
We'll keep you posted.
- Thank you.

08:27.942 --> 08:29.770
Oh, gosh.
[chuckles]

08:29.813 --> 08:30.901
- Okay, I think that I have
every--

08:30.945 --> 08:32.337
[knock at door]

08:32.381 --> 08:33.948
Mr. and Mrs. Bennett,
this is Dr. Hammer.

08:33.991 --> 08:35.079
- Hi.
- Hi.

08:35.123 --> 08:36.298
- I feel okay.

08:36.341 --> 08:37.778
I really--I don't think
I need to be here.

08:37.821 --> 08:40.258
- Honey, you had a seizure.

08:40.302 --> 08:41.346
- Mrs. Bennett
was getting ready

08:41.390 --> 08:43.044
for work when it happened.

08:43.087 --> 08:45.002
The seizure resolved on its own
before the paramedics arrived.

08:45.046 --> 08:47.265
She's COVID-negative
but is running a fever of 102.

08:47.309 --> 08:49.964
- Okay, any history
of epilepsy, seizures?

08:50.007 --> 08:52.270
- No. First time.
But I didn't sleep well.

08:52.314 --> 08:53.489
Could it just be that?

08:53.533 --> 08:55.360
- I don't know.
We're gonna take a look.

08:55.404 --> 08:58.189
Dr. Taylor?
- Yes.

08:58.233 --> 08:59.495
- Do you want me
to call your office,

08:59.539 --> 09:01.105
let them know
you're not coming in?

09:01.149 --> 09:03.238
- No, no. I'll be fine.
I'll take care of it.

09:03.281 --> 09:05.066
- She's never missed
a day of work.

09:05.109 --> 09:06.807
- Stressful job?

09:06.850 --> 09:07.808
- A little.
- Yeah.

09:07.851 --> 09:09.287
They totally depend on her.

09:12.552 --> 09:14.989
- Okay. Lungs are clear.
Heart sounds good.

09:15.032 --> 09:16.947
- Pupils are equal
and reactive.

09:17.992 --> 09:19.602
- Ow. Ow.

09:19.646 --> 09:21.299
- Your liver
is slightly enlarged.

09:21.343 --> 09:23.084
Dr. Taylor,
what do you recommend?

09:23.127 --> 09:25.042
- A CBC, BMP,
and a chest X-ray.

09:25.086 --> 09:26.914
- Is that all really necessary?

09:26.957 --> 09:28.219
- Yeah, I think so.

09:28.263 --> 09:30.134
- I'm sorry, but admissions
just informed me

09:30.178 --> 09:31.962
that there's a problem
with your insurance.

09:32.006 --> 09:33.268
It's not going through.

09:33.311 --> 09:34.486
- Well, that doesn't
make any sense.

09:34.530 --> 09:36.488
She has great coverage
through her work.

09:36.532 --> 09:39.535
- I'll get it sorted out.

09:39.579 --> 09:41.842
- Here, in the meantime,
just put any charges

09:41.885 --> 09:43.278
on our credit card.

09:43.321 --> 09:45.628
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

09:45.672 --> 09:48.326
- We'll check back in as soon
as we get those test results.

09:48.370 --> 09:52.940
<i>♪</i>

09:52.983 --> 09:54.071
- What do we got?

09:54.115 --> 09:55.507
- 28-year-old male
Kyle Liddell.

09:55.551 --> 09:57.248
Fell on the pavement,
struck his head.

09:57.292 --> 09:58.772
- The guy stepped out
in front of a bus.

09:58.815 --> 10:00.991
Good Samaritan turning off
his car alarm pulled him away.

10:01.035 --> 10:02.514
Caused Liddell to fall
and hit his noggin.

10:02.558 --> 10:04.255
- Bystanders say it looked like
he was unconscious

10:04.299 --> 10:06.127
for about a minute.
GCS of 12 now.

10:06.170 --> 10:08.129
Minor hematoma.
No other trauma noted.

10:08.172 --> 10:12.046
- Mr. Liddell, can you hear me?
Mr. Liddell? In here.

10:12.089 --> 10:18.661
<i>♪</i>

10:18.705 --> 10:20.358
All right, on my count.

10:20.402 --> 10:24.014
Ready, one, two, three.

10:24.058 --> 10:26.669
All right. All right.

10:26.713 --> 10:28.540
Let's get some ice
for this goose egg here.

10:28.584 --> 10:30.238
- Right.
- Excuse me.

10:32.153 --> 10:34.329
Does this hurt?
Can you feel this, Mr. Liddell?

10:34.372 --> 10:36.984
- Liddell. I'm Liddell.

10:37.027 --> 10:38.681
- Okay, he's still
pretty out of it.

10:38.725 --> 10:42.293
All right, let's pan scan him,
but first, routine trauma labs,

10:42.337 --> 10:44.948
and I need X-rays
for chest and pelvis.

10:44.992 --> 10:46.341
- X-ray!

10:48.038 --> 10:50.214
- So, suicide attempt?

10:50.258 --> 10:53.217
- Who else steps out
in front of a bus?

10:53.261 --> 10:55.611
- June, let's place him in soft
restraints, just to be safe.

10:55.655 --> 10:57.961
And also, let's place
a psych tech outside his room.

10:58.005 --> 10:59.310
- Got it.

10:59.354 --> 11:01.051
- And also,
let's call Dr. Charles.

11:01.095 --> 11:02.400
- Mm-hmm.

11:09.190 --> 11:11.366
- Mr. Liddell? Kyle?

11:11.409 --> 11:14.021
How you doing, Kyle?
I'm Dr. Charles.

11:14.064 --> 11:16.893
- I'm late. God, I'm late.

11:16.937 --> 11:18.547
Oh, God, I'm late.

11:18.590 --> 11:20.157
- You're late?
What are you late for?

11:20.201 --> 11:22.159
- What the--what is this? Why?

11:22.203 --> 11:23.639
- Well, we were
a little concerned

11:23.683 --> 11:25.119
for your--for your well-being

11:25.162 --> 11:27.077
when you were brought
into the hospital.

11:27.121 --> 11:29.253
- The hospital?
Wait, why I am here?

11:29.297 --> 11:31.647
- Well, you know, you stepped
into a busy street,

11:31.691 --> 11:33.257
and when you were pulled
out of the traffic,

11:33.301 --> 11:34.519
you hit your head.

11:34.563 --> 11:36.434
You're actually very lucky
you didn't sustain

11:36.478 --> 11:38.393
a much more serious injury.

11:38.436 --> 11:40.308
- But no. Uh.

11:40.351 --> 11:42.571
Traffic? I was on campus.

11:42.614 --> 11:43.920
God, I'm late. I have to--
- Okay.

11:43.964 --> 11:46.270
- Please let me go.
- Hold on. Hold on.

11:46.314 --> 11:47.315
Help me understand this.

11:47.358 --> 11:48.490
You said that you
were on campus?

11:48.533 --> 11:50.927
- Yeah. I teach.
- Okay.

11:50.971 --> 11:55.018
'Cause you were actually in
the middle of downtown Chicago.

11:55.062 --> 11:57.542
- No. No.
I--but the--I heard the bells.

11:57.586 --> 11:58.761
- The bells?

11:58.805 --> 11:59.936
Are you--are you
sure about that?

11:59.980 --> 12:01.677
- Yes.

12:01.721 --> 12:03.418
- You know, it says
that the man who--

12:03.461 --> 12:04.636
who pulled you out of traffic

12:04.680 --> 12:06.943
was--was turning
off his car alarm.

12:06.987 --> 12:08.553
Is it possible that
that's what you heard?

12:08.597 --> 12:11.078
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

12:11.121 --> 12:13.297
- Oh, no.

12:13.341 --> 12:15.299
Oh, no. Is it happening again?

12:15.343 --> 12:17.562
- Is--is what happening again?

12:17.606 --> 12:19.477
- I had it under control.

12:19.521 --> 12:20.609
Oh, no, no, no. Come on.

12:20.652 --> 12:22.089
- Tell me what you had
under control.

12:22.132 --> 12:24.569
- I, uh, I have schizophrenia.
And--

12:24.613 --> 12:26.093
- Okay. Okay.

12:26.136 --> 12:27.659
- Oh, God, the voices.
No, no, no.

12:27.703 --> 12:29.966
- Have you been
prescribed medication?

12:30.010 --> 12:31.272
- Yeah, risperidone.

12:31.315 --> 12:33.013
And I--I have been--
I've been taking it.

12:33.056 --> 12:34.231
- That's great.
Who is your doctor?

12:34.275 --> 12:35.276
Who's taking care of you?

12:35.319 --> 12:37.278
- Dr. Kallejian. Henry.

12:37.321 --> 12:39.759
- Okay.
Look, I know Dr. Kallejian.

12:39.802 --> 12:41.586
- Why don't you let me
get in touch with him, okay?

12:41.630 --> 12:43.632
And in the meantime,
gonna give you something

12:43.675 --> 12:45.416
make you feel
a little bit better.

12:45.460 --> 12:49.116
And we will get you
through this, all right?

12:49.159 --> 12:50.204
Nice to meet you, Kyle.

12:50.247 --> 12:51.466
- Nice to meet you.

12:54.817 --> 12:56.645
- So your patient
is not suicidal.

12:56.688 --> 12:58.299
- Oh, yeah?
How do you figure that?

12:58.342 --> 13:00.170
- Well, didn't know he was
stepping into traffic.

13:00.214 --> 13:01.563
- Ah, okay, so the cars

13:01.606 --> 13:03.043
and the busses
didn't tip him off?

13:03.086 --> 13:05.262
- He was having an auditory
hallucination.

13:05.306 --> 13:07.699
Led him to believe he was
on the campus where he teaches.

13:07.743 --> 13:09.571
He--he suffers
from schizophrenia.

13:09.614 --> 13:11.138
- Ah, psychotic.

13:11.181 --> 13:13.270
Well, I've treated his
injuries.

13:13.314 --> 13:14.619
Send him upstairs.

13:14.663 --> 13:16.578
- You know, he's not a danger
to anybody, Dean,

13:16.621 --> 13:18.667
and clearly been
very responsible

13:18.710 --> 13:20.234
about his treatment.

13:20.277 --> 13:22.366
Something destabilized him,
so I'm just gonna--gonna

13:22.410 --> 13:23.715
keep him down here
till I figure out what.

13:23.759 --> 13:25.413
- Well, I'm sure
you know what's best.

13:25.456 --> 13:28.503
But on behalf of all
of our other patients,

13:28.546 --> 13:31.680
the ED is a frightening
enough place as-is,

13:31.723 --> 13:34.291
but when you add
the mentally ill into the mix,

13:34.335 --> 13:37.251
it can only
compound people's fears.

13:37.294 --> 13:40.820
<i>♪</i>

13:40.863 --> 13:45.346
- Matt.
- Will. My savior.

13:45.389 --> 13:48.044
Man, I was lucky
I was with you, huh?

13:48.088 --> 13:49.350
- How you doing?

13:50.742 --> 13:52.875
- I'm great.

13:52.919 --> 13:55.356
I wish I had something
to offer you other than JELL-O.

13:55.399 --> 13:57.184
- Nah, I'm good. Thanks.

13:57.227 --> 14:00.187
Listen, Matt,
I want to ask you...

14:01.449 --> 14:03.799
Any regrets?

14:03.843 --> 14:05.148
- Regrets?

14:06.541 --> 14:09.196
You mean the coke
and the booze.

14:09.239 --> 14:10.458
Yeah, sure.

14:10.501 --> 14:13.243
- No, come on, man.

14:13.287 --> 14:14.462
The Vas-COM.

14:16.246 --> 14:17.813
- Why would I have
any regrets about that?

14:17.857 --> 14:19.728
- Before your heart attack,

14:19.771 --> 14:22.557
that's what it seemed
like you were saying.

14:22.600 --> 14:23.863
- I was pretty out of it.

14:23.906 --> 14:26.430
I don't really remember
what I said, but no.

14:28.215 --> 14:30.130
I want you to check
this out, though.

14:30.173 --> 14:32.610
Janie and I are renting
a villa in Montenegro.

14:34.569 --> 14:36.658
Okay, two months on the beach.

14:40.444 --> 14:42.185
I mean, I'm thinking
I come back from here,

14:42.229 --> 14:44.796
I'm gonna start a concierge
practice in Montana,

14:44.840 --> 14:46.886
and it's beautiful.

14:46.929 --> 14:49.105
There's so much money there.

14:49.149 --> 14:51.455
Wouldn't have to work so hard.

14:51.499 --> 14:53.109
Right?

14:55.155 --> 14:56.939
- You know, given the degree
of portal hypertension,

14:56.983 --> 14:59.899
we should use
a venovenous bypass

14:59.942 --> 15:01.422
early in the hepatectomy.

15:01.465 --> 15:03.337
- Good catch.

15:03.380 --> 15:05.165
Is that aftershave?

15:05.208 --> 15:06.383
- Excuse me?

15:06.427 --> 15:08.516
- What I'm smelling.

15:08.559 --> 15:10.779
- Does that bother you?

15:10.822 --> 15:11.823
- No.

15:13.564 --> 15:15.740
As long as it's not verbena.

15:15.784 --> 15:17.133
That's what my ex wears.

15:19.179 --> 15:20.267
What else do you see?

15:23.270 --> 15:24.793
- Uh,

15:24.836 --> 15:26.664
yeah, the donated liver
is smaller in size,

15:26.708 --> 15:28.840
so we should oversew.

15:28.884 --> 15:30.451
- Right.
- Right.

15:30.494 --> 15:31.800
[alarm blaring]

15:31.843 --> 15:33.280
- Dr. Blake.

15:33.323 --> 15:34.629
Mr. Carmona's crashing.

15:34.672 --> 15:36.979
<i>[tense music]</i>

15:37.023 --> 15:39.286
- Reuben, mi amor.
- What's going on?

15:39.329 --> 15:40.765
- I don't know.

15:40.809 --> 15:43.464
He started talking funny,
not making any sense at all.

15:43.507 --> 15:45.945
- And then
he just stopped moving.

15:45.988 --> 15:48.817
- Reuben?
Can you open your eyes?

15:48.860 --> 15:50.819
Reuben. Open your eyes.

15:50.862 --> 15:53.865
- Oh, God.
- Reuben?

15:53.909 --> 15:55.606
All right, GCS 7. Let's go.

15:55.650 --> 15:57.217
- We gotta get his CO2 down.

15:57.260 --> 15:58.827
Get an intubation kit ready.
Bag mask.

15:58.870 --> 16:00.263
- He needs a CT stat.

16:00.307 --> 16:01.743
And let radiology know
we're coming up.

16:01.786 --> 16:03.484
- What's happened to him?
- Not sure.

16:03.527 --> 16:05.399
Hopefully we'll know
after the CT.

16:05.442 --> 16:07.183
- What about the transplant?

16:07.227 --> 16:08.576
- Believe me, we're gonna do
everything we can to make sure

16:08.619 --> 16:09.707
he gets that surgery, okay?

16:09.751 --> 16:11.318
Kate, would you
direct the family

16:11.361 --> 16:13.581
to the waiting center, please?

16:13.624 --> 16:16.279
Ready? Here we go, guys.

16:16.323 --> 16:17.498
[knock at door]

16:17.541 --> 16:18.586
- Come in.

16:20.980 --> 16:23.330
So you informed the board?

16:23.373 --> 16:24.679
- I did.

16:24.722 --> 16:27.029
They're very grateful
you and Dr. Halstead

16:27.073 --> 16:29.336
uncovered this fraud.

16:29.379 --> 16:30.467
- Okay.

16:30.511 --> 16:32.208
- And they see a way,
going forward,

16:32.252 --> 16:35.037
that will protect
the interests of the hospital.

16:35.081 --> 16:36.778
- What is that supposed
to mean?

16:36.821 --> 16:38.867
- Dr. Cooper will be fired
immediately, and Chicago Med

16:38.910 --> 16:41.348
will discontinue use
of all Vasik equipment.

16:41.391 --> 16:44.655
- And that's it?
- What about the FBI?

16:44.699 --> 16:45.961
- The board does not feel

16:46.005 --> 16:47.702
that is in the hospital's
best interests.

16:47.745 --> 16:49.269
- You've gotta be kidding me.

16:49.312 --> 16:51.749
- Sharon, you and I both know
that these things are

16:51.793 --> 16:53.969
best dealt with quietly.

16:54.013 --> 16:56.450
- The board doesn't want
the negative publicity.

16:56.493 --> 16:58.843
- With good reason.
Look at the ramifications.

16:58.887 --> 17:00.628
Loss of donors,
A-list physicians leaving.

17:00.671 --> 17:01.890
It's devastating.

17:01.933 --> 17:04.675
- So I imagine
Dr. Cooper's father-in-law

17:04.719 --> 17:06.460
had his hand in this.

17:06.503 --> 17:09.376
- Of course he did.
So Matt Cooper just walks?

17:09.419 --> 17:11.378
And what about all those
other Vasik execs?

17:11.421 --> 17:13.902
- The board is just thinking
of the greater good.

17:13.945 --> 17:15.382
- Whose greater good?

17:15.425 --> 17:17.427
- I understand how you feel,
how you both feel.

17:17.471 --> 17:20.343
But the decision has been made.
There's no appeal, all right?

17:20.387 --> 17:22.606
So I advise that
we keep this to ourselves.

17:22.650 --> 17:24.608
There is no sense
in jeopardizing

17:24.652 --> 17:26.915
our employment, okay?
This is over.

17:26.958 --> 17:29.439
Let's go back to work.
Put this behind us.

17:29.483 --> 17:35.967
<i>♪</i>

17:37.012 --> 17:40.015
- Hell, I'll go to the FBI.
- You can't go to the FBI.

17:40.059 --> 17:41.408
- Sure, I can.

17:41.451 --> 17:42.887
Your whole purpose
in bringing me here

17:42.931 --> 17:44.106
was to get evidence
to take to them.

17:44.150 --> 17:45.455
- And you did that.

17:45.499 --> 17:48.328
- You validated my suspicions,
and I thank you.

17:48.371 --> 17:49.894
- Okay, Matt is planning
to set up shop

17:49.938 --> 17:51.722
in a billionaire enclave
in Montana.

17:51.766 --> 17:54.943
- You know, he can
plan anything he wants.

17:54.986 --> 17:56.466
- All due respect,
Ms. Goodwin--

17:56.510 --> 17:57.859
- Dr. Halstead, you came to me

17:57.902 --> 17:59.339
because you wanted
your job back.

17:59.382 --> 18:01.950
You got it.
Now, this is over.

18:01.993 --> 18:05.388
It's time for you
to focus on medicine.

18:05.432 --> 18:12.439
<i>♪</i>

18:24.015 --> 18:25.974
- I'm seeing diffuse
brain edema.

18:26.017 --> 18:27.497
- Yeah, it's the end-stage
liver failure.

18:27.541 --> 18:28.977
- And his transplant surgery?

18:29.020 --> 18:31.240
- Well, there's signs
of impending brain herniation.

18:31.284 --> 18:33.503
If we don't correct it,
you can forget transplant.

18:33.547 --> 18:35.157
This man will be dead.

18:35.201 --> 18:37.812
- Can we correct it?

18:37.855 --> 18:39.988
- How much longer is
the donor liver viable?

18:40.031 --> 18:42.121
- Four hours, tops.

18:42.164 --> 18:43.557
- It's possible.

18:43.600 --> 18:45.080
I can put a right-front bolt
with a twist drill

18:45.124 --> 18:46.951
to monitor
intracranial pressure

18:46.995 --> 18:49.171
while treating with mannitol
and hypertonic saline,

18:49.215 --> 18:51.739
along with the lactulose
and rifaximin.

18:51.782 --> 18:52.870
- And that should bring
the pressure down

18:52.914 --> 18:54.263
so we can operate, right?

18:54.307 --> 18:55.569
- Yeah, that's the idea.

18:55.612 --> 18:57.179
Even though you had the good
sense to call me,

18:57.223 --> 18:58.789
I can't guarantee anything.

18:58.833 --> 19:01.792
<i>[suspenseful music]</i>

19:01.836 --> 19:08.712
<i>♪</i>

19:10.540 --> 19:13.108
- She's worse.
- Terrible headache.

19:13.152 --> 19:15.632
- Temperature's 104.

19:15.676 --> 19:17.156
- Jaundice.

19:17.199 --> 19:20.159
- Ow! Really hurts now.
- What--what's wrong with her?

19:20.202 --> 19:21.725
- I'm sorry, her tests
weren't conclusive.

19:21.769 --> 19:23.771
- Start her on a broad
spectrum antibiotic?

19:23.814 --> 19:25.512
- With these symptoms, there's
a multitude of possible causes,

19:25.555 --> 19:26.948
and I don't like
prescribing antibiotics

19:26.991 --> 19:28.689
unless they're
absolutely necessary.

19:28.732 --> 19:30.560
I think we should hold off till
we know what we're treating.

19:30.604 --> 19:32.780
- But you--you said her tests
weren't conclusive.

19:32.823 --> 19:33.824
- Yeah, I'd like to send her
for a CT

19:33.868 --> 19:35.391
of her chest and her abdomen.

19:35.435 --> 19:37.088
It'll give us a much clearer
picture of what's going on.

19:37.132 --> 19:38.220
- How much will that cost?

19:38.264 --> 19:39.656
- What difference does
that make?

19:39.700 --> 19:40.875
Yes. Yes. Of course.

19:40.918 --> 19:43.007
- Okay, you can do with her.
- Thank you.

19:43.051 --> 19:45.880
- I need a transporter.

19:45.923 --> 19:48.839
Hey, so we need to send Eve
up to Radiology.

19:48.883 --> 19:50.667
- I'm sorry, but admissions
just informed me

19:50.711 --> 19:52.626
that your credit card
was declined.

19:52.669 --> 19:55.194
- What?
No, I hardly ever use that.

19:55.237 --> 19:57.065
- I can see that your wife
is going up for tests.

19:57.108 --> 19:58.197
We can deal with this later.

19:58.240 --> 20:00.242
- Yeah. Thank you.

20:00.286 --> 20:07.249
<i>♪</i>

20:13.168 --> 20:14.256
- How you feeling?

20:14.300 --> 20:16.258
- Better, yeah. Tired.

20:16.302 --> 20:17.651
- Yeah?
- Yeah.

20:17.694 --> 20:19.261
- Probably the sedation.

20:19.305 --> 20:20.567
You know what?

20:20.610 --> 20:22.351
I don't think
we need these anymore.

20:22.395 --> 20:24.092
Would you?

20:25.833 --> 20:27.226
- Wow.
- So...

20:27.269 --> 20:28.966
- Oh, wow. Thank you.
- I talked to Dr. Kallejian.

20:29.010 --> 20:30.359
- Uh-huh.

20:30.403 --> 20:31.839
- He says that you've been
managing your illness

20:31.882 --> 20:34.015
really well
over the last few years.

20:34.058 --> 20:36.060
Which leads me to wonder--
I mean, any--

20:36.104 --> 20:38.933
any big changes
in your life recently,

20:38.976 --> 20:42.719
like, I don't know, new job?
Loss of a loved one?

20:42.763 --> 20:43.938
- I'm not married.

20:43.981 --> 20:45.200
Both my parents are still
alive.

20:45.244 --> 20:46.288
We're close.

20:46.332 --> 20:47.898
- That's good.
- Yeah.

20:47.942 --> 20:50.031
I've been a doctoral candidate
for the last two years.

20:50.074 --> 20:51.293
Been TA-ing the whole time.

20:51.337 --> 20:53.600
- Okay.

20:53.643 --> 20:55.297
- Is this gonna keep, like,
happening?

20:55.341 --> 20:56.733
Is this gonna get worse?

20:56.777 --> 20:57.952
- Not if I can help it.
- Okay.

20:57.995 --> 20:59.780
- I mean, my plan
is to figure out what--

20:59.823 --> 21:03.131
what caused your episode
and to address it.

21:03.174 --> 21:06.134
Kyle, any new medications
of any kind?

21:06.177 --> 21:07.309
- No.

21:07.353 --> 21:08.919
- Okay.
- No, no, no. No.

21:08.963 --> 21:11.095
Look, I can't end up back
in the hospital again.

21:11.139 --> 21:13.707
- Nobody's talking about that.
Nobody.

21:13.750 --> 21:17.624
No new vitamins or supplements?

21:17.667 --> 21:20.801
- No, I take--I take, like,
Vitamin D, fish oil.

21:20.844 --> 21:24.370
- Well, those are both good.
Anything--anything else?

21:24.413 --> 21:28.765
- Oh, I started drinking this
tea like a month or two ago.

21:28.809 --> 21:30.027
- Hmm.

21:30.071 --> 21:31.072
- I go to this health
food store near me.

21:31.115 --> 21:32.247
They blend their own.

21:32.291 --> 21:34.728
I drink one called
Mindful Energy.

21:34.771 --> 21:35.990
It's supposed to help you
focus,

21:36.033 --> 21:37.426
you know, keep you sharp.

21:37.470 --> 21:39.776
- Can you remember the name
of the health food store?

21:39.820 --> 21:41.256
- Yeah, Happy Path.

21:41.300 --> 21:43.389
- Okay, well, listen,
I want you to rest some more,

21:43.432 --> 21:46.914
but we are making
progress here, okay?

21:46.957 --> 21:48.742
I'm really glad to see
that you're feeling better.

21:55.183 --> 21:57.968
- So what's the deal?

21:58.012 --> 22:01.755
Can we turf Liddell
out of my ED or what?

22:01.798 --> 22:03.757
- You know, Dean, I gotta say,
hard not to notice

22:03.800 --> 22:06.455
that you don't have
a whole lot of patience

22:06.499 --> 22:07.848
with mental illness, do you?

22:07.891 --> 22:09.980
- You noticed that, have you?

22:10.024 --> 22:11.373
- Yeah.
- You know Kyle, here,

22:11.417 --> 22:16.726
and you know our patient
Krista, those twins, Neil.

22:16.770 --> 22:19.773
- Yeah, you just, you can't
let go of that, can you?

22:19.816 --> 22:21.340
All right, let me give you
my perspective here.

22:21.383 --> 22:23.167
Okay, when you're in combat
and you're dealing

22:23.211 --> 22:26.997
with the wounded, they can say
some pretty crazy things.

22:27.041 --> 22:30.087
You don't listen to them.
You just get them to safety.

22:30.131 --> 22:32.394
And you do everything
you can to save their lives.

22:32.438 --> 22:35.005
- I completely get that. I do.

22:35.049 --> 22:36.442
But, I mean,
just for the record,

22:36.485 --> 22:39.183
trauma-induced mania, I mean,
it's temporary.

22:39.227 --> 22:40.489
It's not a mental illness.

22:40.533 --> 22:42.186
- Look, you can split hairs
all you want.

22:42.230 --> 22:43.492
What about Liddell?

22:43.536 --> 22:45.102
- You know, I still have
some digging to do,

22:45.146 --> 22:50.369
but I have to say I am really
developing a--I don't know,

22:50.412 --> 22:53.110
an admiration for his--
for this courage.

22:53.154 --> 22:56.026
- Courage?
- Yeah.

22:56.070 --> 22:57.332
You got a couple minutes?

22:57.376 --> 22:59.378
I'd like to show you
what I--what I mean.

23:01.510 --> 23:03.207
- Sure.

23:05.993 --> 23:07.211
- You know, it's a simulation

23:07.255 --> 23:09.431
that was developed
for psych residents.

23:11.259 --> 23:13.174
Give them a sense of what
some of their patients

23:13.217 --> 23:14.958
were experiencing.
- Yeah.

23:15.002 --> 23:17.439
- Look, gets too intense, just,
you know, take them off, okay?

23:17.483 --> 23:21.225
- No, I'm sure it'll be fine.
- All right.

23:21.269 --> 23:24.228
I gotta go back upstairs.

23:24.272 --> 23:27.014
But I'd love to check in
with you later,

23:27.057 --> 23:28.450
see what you thought?
- All right.

23:28.494 --> 23:30.147
[clears throat]
- Okay.

23:32.454 --> 23:37.241
- Wow. Huh. Look at that.

23:37.285 --> 23:39.069
<i>- You should never have left
your apartment.</i>

23:39.113 --> 23:41.158
<i>They can get you out here.
You have no protection.</i>

23:41.202 --> 23:42.421
- Ha.

23:42.464 --> 23:44.248
<i>[tense music]</i>

23:44.292 --> 23:46.207
<i>- You're so stupid. Worthless.</i>

23:46.250 --> 23:47.208
<i>Everybody knows it.</i>

23:47.251 --> 23:49.471
<i>[indistinct whispering]</i>

23:49.515 --> 23:53.083
<i>Why did you listen?
You're in danger.</i>

23:53.127 --> 23:56.870
<i>Don't look at them.
Don't make eye contact.</i>

23:56.913 --> 23:59.176
<i>They hate you.
Everybody hates you.</i>

23:59.220 --> 24:01.483
<i>She's one of them.
She's getting instructions.</i>

24:04.225 --> 24:07.228
<i>Those are poison.
Don't touch them.</i>

24:07.271 --> 24:10.536
<i>You're evil.
You don't deserve to eat.</i>

24:12.233 --> 24:14.017
<i>Stay back. They'll kill you.</i>

24:14.061 --> 24:15.410
- Uh...

24:15.454 --> 24:18.239
<i>- You're hopeless. Pathetic.
A waste of time.</i>

24:18.282 --> 24:22.504
<i>You're such a failure.
Look at you. You suck.</i>

24:22.548 --> 24:25.855
<i>You should die.
We'd all be better off.</i>

24:25.899 --> 24:27.248
- [gasps]

24:27.291 --> 24:31.992
<i>♪</i>

24:37.780 --> 24:40.522
- Well?
- ICP is down, but still high.

24:40.566 --> 24:42.655
- So he's improved.
- Marginally.

24:42.698 --> 24:44.657
- Well, given what I had
to work with.

24:44.700 --> 24:45.745
- I know, Sam.

24:45.788 --> 24:47.486
- Okay, but with a new liver,

24:47.529 --> 24:49.575
Reuben's encephalopathy
and edema might well resolve.

24:49.618 --> 24:51.315
- Or they could get worse
from the surgery

24:51.359 --> 24:53.492
and lead to a herniation.

24:53.535 --> 24:54.710
- If you hold off
on the transplant,

24:54.754 --> 24:56.886
I can do a hemicraniectomy
for the edema.

24:56.930 --> 24:58.888
- No, with the donor
liver's window of viability,

24:58.932 --> 25:01.674
we can't wait.
We have to operate now.

25:01.717 --> 25:02.892
- Or you find a new liver.

25:02.936 --> 25:04.415
- No, Reuben's blood type
is rare.

25:04.459 --> 25:06.505
He'll die before
he gets another match.

25:06.548 --> 25:10.291
<i>[tense music]</i>

25:10.334 --> 25:11.858
- I say we go for it.

25:13.686 --> 25:14.948
- It's our best option.

25:18.952 --> 25:20.344
[baby crying]

25:20.388 --> 25:21.911
- Dr. Halstead, Dr. Scott.

25:21.955 --> 25:25.001
[alarm blaring]

25:25.045 --> 25:26.525
- Help her! Please!

25:26.568 --> 25:28.309
- She was doing so good.

25:28.352 --> 25:30.659
- 50 mg/kg of phenobarb.
- Got it.

25:30.703 --> 25:32.618
- Heartrate 130.
Sats are down to 86.

25:32.661 --> 25:34.533
Caprice, bag her.

25:34.576 --> 25:36.360
- I'll set her up to intubate.
- Intubate?

25:36.404 --> 25:37.927
- Lily can't protect her airway
right now.

25:37.971 --> 25:39.581
But intubation
is the safest thing for her.

25:39.625 --> 25:41.757
- Oh, my God.
- Broselow was in the pink.

25:41.801 --> 25:44.847
Give me 2 mg of etomidate
and 13 mg of sux.

25:44.891 --> 25:47.807
- Satting now at 94.
- Why is this happening?

25:47.850 --> 25:49.896
- I promise we're gonna
find out, okay?

25:49.939 --> 25:51.941
Now, let me know when
those drugs are in.

25:51.985 --> 25:57.991
<i>♪</i>

25:58.034 --> 25:59.296
- Okay,
so with your permission,

25:59.340 --> 26:01.255
we'd like to send Lily
for a CT of her head.

26:01.298 --> 26:03.953
- Anything. Just make her well.

26:07.957 --> 26:10.394
- Scans didn't reveal
any tumors, masses,

26:10.438 --> 26:12.614
or obvious infections.

26:12.658 --> 26:13.920
Any ideas?

26:15.835 --> 26:18.751
- One. Kind of a stretch.

26:18.794 --> 26:20.579
Something I saw
when I was homeless.

26:20.622 --> 26:22.972
- This couple isn't
experiencing homelessness.

26:23.016 --> 26:24.800
- No.

26:24.844 --> 26:26.585
No, there's something going on.

26:27.977 --> 26:30.589
I need to give her
a more thorough physical exam.

26:30.632 --> 26:37.334
<i>♪</i>

26:39.641 --> 26:41.643
- Sepsis?
- Yeah, possibly.

26:41.687 --> 26:43.689
But she's not running a fever.

26:43.732 --> 26:46.300
- Okay, so stroke.
Intracranial hemorrhage?

26:46.343 --> 26:49.346
- Yeah, I mean, CT
should tell us something.

26:54.395 --> 26:55.918
- Poor little girl.

26:55.962 --> 26:57.833
What'd she ever do
to deserve this?

26:57.877 --> 27:04.884
<i>♪</i>

27:19.115 --> 27:20.726
- Just turn your head.

27:24.730 --> 27:27.602
Here. Here, take a look.

27:30.083 --> 27:32.476
- What is it?
- A scab.

27:32.520 --> 27:33.869
It's from an insect bite.

27:36.698 --> 27:37.786
- What does that mean?

27:37.830 --> 27:39.092
- I have an idea,
but I'm not sure.

27:39.135 --> 27:40.528
I need to run
one more test.

27:40.571 --> 27:42.965
- Western blot analysis?
- Yeah.

27:43.009 --> 27:44.706
We should have
an answer very soon.

27:48.667 --> 27:50.669
- So I called
your health food store,

27:50.712 --> 27:51.887
and I got the ingredients

27:51.931 --> 27:53.715
to that tea
you've been drinking.

27:53.759 --> 27:55.586
Lot of stuff in there.

27:55.630 --> 27:58.981
I think yerba mate,
spearmint extract.

27:59.025 --> 28:01.375
But the main ingredient
is St. John's wort.

28:01.418 --> 28:03.116
Now, listen, nothing wrong

28:03.159 --> 28:04.726
with St. John's wort,
per se, right?

28:04.770 --> 28:06.728
Actually helpful to--
to some people.

28:06.772 --> 28:09.688
But it has also been known
to increase the metabolism

28:09.731 --> 28:13.169
of certain
antipsychotic medications.

28:13.213 --> 28:14.867
- Increase the metabolism?
- Yeah.

28:14.910 --> 28:17.478
It speeds up how your
body processes them, right?

28:17.521 --> 28:20.873
Rendering them
considerably less effective.

28:20.916 --> 28:22.483
- So I'm gonna be okay?

28:22.526 --> 28:25.007
- You switch out that tea,
yeah, I believe you will be.

28:25.051 --> 28:26.835
I mean, look,
you responded really well

28:26.879 --> 28:29.838
to the extra risperidone
I gave you, right?

28:29.882 --> 28:32.580
Half-life of St. John's wort
is, like, 24 hours,

28:32.623 --> 28:33.842
so by this time tomorrow,

28:33.886 --> 28:36.062
you should be feeling
a whole lot better.

28:38.020 --> 28:40.806
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

28:40.849 --> 28:43.809
<i>[heartfelt music]</i>

28:43.852 --> 28:47.203
<i>♪</i>

28:47.247 --> 28:50.032
- Okay, done clamping.
- Initiate VV bypass.

28:50.076 --> 28:51.033
[machine beeping]

28:51.077 --> 28:52.643
- ICP's up in the 70s.

28:52.687 --> 28:54.123
- We gotta get that
ICP below 20.

28:54.167 --> 28:56.560
Let me do a hemicraniectomy
now, before he herniates.

28:56.604 --> 29:00.608
- No, we need to complete
the transplant first.

29:00.651 --> 29:02.566
- With a new liver,
things will correct with time.

29:02.610 --> 29:04.568
- Or you'll have a working
liver in a braindead patient.

29:04.612 --> 29:08.572
<i>[tense music]</i>

29:08.616 --> 29:10.618
- Treat him medically
while we operate.

29:14.665 --> 29:16.493
- Dr. Abrams?

29:19.496 --> 29:22.586
- 1 g/kg mannitol, increase
propofol to burst suppress,

29:22.630 --> 29:23.805
and replace clotting factors.

29:27.504 --> 29:29.202
- Good.
- Last one.

29:33.641 --> 29:34.860
Let's get this liver out.

29:40.517 --> 29:43.259
- I'm sorry, but we believe
Lily has a genetic condition

29:43.303 --> 29:45.218
called OTC deficiency,

29:45.261 --> 29:48.482
which causes ammonia
to build up in the blood.

29:48.525 --> 29:51.050
We're ordering
a specific lab to confirm.

29:51.093 --> 29:54.749
- If it's genetic, why is
she just getting sick now?

29:54.793 --> 29:56.098
- The disease can
present anywhere

29:56.142 --> 29:58.840
from a few days after birth
to several months.

29:58.884 --> 30:01.625
- How serious is it?
- Unfortunately, very.

30:01.669 --> 30:03.584
We need to start
treatment immediately.

30:05.151 --> 30:07.980
- Is our little girl gonna die?

30:08.023 --> 30:09.590
- We're gonna do
everything we can

30:09.633 --> 30:10.809
to make sure
that doesn't happen.

30:14.334 --> 30:18.120
- Let's get Lily up to PICU,
get her on hemodialysis.

30:18.164 --> 30:24.735
<i>♪</i>

30:24.779 --> 30:28.696
- Hey.
So we got your test results.

30:28.739 --> 30:31.786
You contracted a disease
called typhus.

30:31.830 --> 30:33.657
- Typhus.

30:33.701 --> 30:35.703
In the United States?

30:35.746 --> 30:37.705
- It does occur,
and we can treat it.

30:37.748 --> 30:39.968
- Doxycycline 500 mg.

30:40.012 --> 30:42.753
- How the hell
did she get typhus?

30:42.797 --> 30:44.277
- From a flea bite.

30:44.320 --> 30:45.887
That was the scab
that we found.

30:45.931 --> 30:48.847
Most likely it was a flea that
had been on an infected rat.

30:48.890 --> 30:50.631
- What does it matter
how I got it?

30:50.674 --> 30:53.112
- It matters.
It's a public health issue.

30:53.155 --> 30:54.983
- I'm sorry, I have no idea.

30:57.159 --> 31:00.032
- Eve, enough.

31:00.075 --> 31:02.817
I want to know what's going on.

31:02.861 --> 31:04.166
- What do you mean?

31:04.210 --> 31:06.560
- Your health insurance
isn't valid,

31:06.603 --> 31:08.257
our credit cards are maxed out,

31:08.301 --> 31:12.348
and you've come down
with typhus from a rat.

31:12.392 --> 31:14.133
Eve, tell me.

31:17.963 --> 31:19.878
- I haven't--

31:19.921 --> 31:21.836
I haven't been going
into the office

31:21.880 --> 31:23.055
for the past three months.

31:24.795 --> 31:29.061
I spend my days
in our storage locker.

31:29.104 --> 31:32.934
<i>[solemn music]</i>

31:32.978 --> 31:34.675
- Our storage locker?

31:36.242 --> 31:38.809
- My company's restructuring.

31:38.853 --> 31:41.160
They fired me.

31:41.203 --> 31:45.077
I've been trying to find
another job, and there's...

31:45.120 --> 31:47.993
[voice breaking]
There's nothing. Nothing.

31:48.036 --> 31:51.344
- Why didn't you just tell me?
- Because I couldn't!

31:51.387 --> 31:54.695
Everybody thinks
I'm this huge success.

31:59.091 --> 32:00.788
You think I am.

32:05.445 --> 32:09.362
- Honey.
- I'm sorry. I'm so ashamed.

32:09.405 --> 32:12.365
- No.

32:12.408 --> 32:13.932
- I'm sorry.

32:15.716 --> 32:19.111
I'm so--I'm so sorry.

32:30.949 --> 32:33.777
- I was wondering
where you got to.

32:37.520 --> 32:39.740
- It was unsettling, you know?

32:39.783 --> 32:41.089
- Yeah.

32:43.135 --> 32:45.920
- How does he--

32:45.964 --> 32:47.443
how does Liddell do it?

32:49.271 --> 32:50.881
Everything going on
inside of him like that.

32:50.925 --> 32:52.666
How does he--
how does he hold a job?

32:52.709 --> 32:54.624
How does he get
through the day?

32:56.148 --> 32:57.453
- I mean, I think he works
at it, you know?

32:57.497 --> 32:59.586
He stays on top of it.

32:59.629 --> 33:01.762
Goes to therapy.

33:01.805 --> 33:04.373
Takes his meds.

33:04.417 --> 33:08.682
Look, I've known
a lot of individuals

33:08.725 --> 33:11.293
been faced with serious
mental health challenges,

33:11.337 --> 33:12.599
right,
who get the help they need

33:12.642 --> 33:16.429
and go on to lead full,
normal lives.

33:16.472 --> 33:18.735
I'm talking about people
with severe depression,

33:18.779 --> 33:21.521
with PTSD, you know?

33:24.219 --> 33:28.963
I understand
how terrifying it must be.

33:29.007 --> 33:31.444
- What?

33:31.487 --> 33:32.271
- Well...

33:33.750 --> 33:35.709
For a soldier to ask for help,
right?

33:35.752 --> 33:39.713
For a soldier to think
that they might be one of them.

33:41.367 --> 33:43.543
You know, someone who could

33:43.586 --> 33:45.371
lose it at any second,
fall apart.

33:45.414 --> 33:47.503
- Hey, that's--
that's not gonna happen.

33:49.984 --> 33:51.551
- It's always been
so mysterious to me.

33:51.594 --> 33:54.945
You know, I think about guys
like you and Ethan over there,

33:54.989 --> 33:56.469
doing your jobs.

33:56.512 --> 33:58.906
You guys are, like,

33:58.949 --> 34:01.952
bravest people I'll ever know.

34:01.996 --> 34:05.913
- Mm.
- But when it comes to--

34:05.956 --> 34:07.610
to saving yourselves?

34:09.221 --> 34:10.613
- All right, listen, it's...

34:12.267 --> 34:14.530
It's not always so bad.

34:17.055 --> 34:18.839
Comes and goes.

34:18.882 --> 34:19.883
- Anyway.

34:21.711 --> 34:23.844
I--I get that
it's complicated, okay?

34:23.887 --> 34:27.674
But I just--I just
want you to know,

34:27.717 --> 34:32.026
there's ever anything I can do,
you know I'm around.

34:32.070 --> 34:39.207
<i>♪</i>

34:40.687 --> 34:42.210
- Hey, Dan?

34:45.996 --> 34:47.476
Uh...

34:49.043 --> 34:50.566
I'm sorry about Neil.

34:52.742 --> 34:53.917
I could have done better.

34:59.575 --> 35:01.360
And I'm sorry Ethan got shot.

35:04.580 --> 35:05.755
- I know you are.

35:05.799 --> 35:12.806
<i>♪</i>

35:29.779 --> 35:31.477
- Lily will need
a liver transplant,

35:31.520 --> 35:33.696
but I think
she's out of the woods.

35:33.740 --> 35:35.089
She's responding well
to the medicine

35:35.133 --> 35:37.265
and the dialysis.

35:37.309 --> 35:39.049
I'm hopeful.

35:39.093 --> 35:42.401
- Well, at least
that's something.

35:42.444 --> 35:44.403
- What's going on with you?

35:45.708 --> 35:49.059
- You got a baby, a total
innocent, has to suffer,

35:49.103 --> 35:50.626
while a bunch of crooks
in this world

35:50.670 --> 35:52.367
are getting away
with everything.

35:54.848 --> 35:57.372
I'll see you
at the Christmas party.

35:57.416 --> 35:58.852
Hope the punch is spiked.

35:58.895 --> 36:05.902
<i>♪</i>

36:09.515 --> 36:10.994
- Reuben's surgery
was a success.

36:11.038 --> 36:12.779
- Oh.

36:12.822 --> 36:13.997
- He's doing well.

36:14.041 --> 36:16.435
You'll get to see him
in a couple hours.

36:16.478 --> 36:17.784
- Thank you.

36:25.922 --> 36:30.840
- So a patient gave me this.

36:30.884 --> 36:32.799
- Oh.

36:32.842 --> 36:34.975
- What do you say?
- Absolutely.

36:42.896 --> 36:44.027
- Ooh!

36:53.036 --> 36:54.342
Oh.

36:56.953 --> 36:58.999
Merry Christmas.

36:59.042 --> 37:00.870
- Merry Christmas.

37:06.876 --> 37:09.749
- Oh, wow, look at that.
- Huh.

37:09.792 --> 37:11.403
<i>[heartwarming music]</i>

37:11.446 --> 37:13.187
Mistletoe.

37:13.231 --> 37:14.710
- Yeah.

37:16.538 --> 37:18.932
And two vaccinated,
consenting adults.

37:20.716 --> 37:21.891
- Indeed.

37:21.935 --> 37:28.942
<i>♪</i>

37:34.730 --> 37:37.690
- God, it must have been
so hard to keep that lie up.

37:39.605 --> 37:41.824
I know.

37:41.868 --> 37:43.478
I've done it myself.

37:45.741 --> 37:48.744
I never told anyone
about my mom.

37:48.788 --> 37:50.529
How we lived.

37:50.572 --> 37:54.054
Acted like I had
a perfect little life.

37:54.097 --> 37:55.795
Not easy.

37:58.711 --> 38:00.887
- I've been keeping up
a lie too.

38:04.499 --> 38:05.718
- Yeah.

38:08.286 --> 38:10.113
And it's costing us too much.

38:15.989 --> 38:19.427
<i>[festive music playing]</i>

38:19.471 --> 38:23.605
- Is there a Carly here?
- Who, me?

38:23.649 --> 38:25.912
- [gasps]
Yay!

38:25.955 --> 38:28.088
[chuckles]
Here you go.

38:28.131 --> 38:30.003
- Looks like you've been nice.

38:30.046 --> 38:32.179
- What do you say?
- Thank you!

38:32.222 --> 38:34.834
- You're welcome! Yay!

38:34.877 --> 38:37.967
Mwah! Merry Christmas!

38:38.011 --> 38:39.708
See you later. Okay!

38:42.842 --> 38:45.105
- You know, upstairs,

38:45.148 --> 38:47.281
what happened...
- Mm-hmm.

38:47.325 --> 38:50.502
- That was just for fun.
- Yeah.

38:50.545 --> 38:52.199
Mistletoe.

38:52.242 --> 38:55.594
- Mistletoe. See you tomorrow.

38:55.637 --> 38:57.900
- Okay.

38:57.944 --> 39:01.164
- And last but not least,
where's Cody?

39:01.208 --> 39:03.471
Yay!

39:03.515 --> 39:04.951
Merry Christmas.

39:04.994 --> 39:07.954
[applause]

39:15.309 --> 39:17.659
- Um, Santa, can I say
something real quick?

39:17.703 --> 39:19.182
- Sure. Okay.

39:24.971 --> 39:26.538
- For those of you who
don't know,

39:26.581 --> 39:29.671
and that's most of you, um...

39:33.980 --> 39:37.810
Maggie Lockwood
is my biological mother.

39:37.853 --> 39:41.335
<i>[heartwarming music]</i>

39:41.379 --> 39:46.601
And I am so grateful and
blessed to have her in my life.

39:46.645 --> 39:53.173
<i>♪</i>

39:56.959 --> 39:59.962
[applause]

40:05.881 --> 40:07.927
- Ms. Goodwin?
- Yes.

40:07.970 --> 40:09.668
- Pursuant to our conversation,
we have warrants

40:09.711 --> 40:11.626
for the following offices
and computers.

40:11.670 --> 40:12.975
- Thank you.

40:13.019 --> 40:16.022
<i>[tense music]</i>

40:16.065 --> 40:18.067
- Matthew Cooper,
you're under arrest

40:18.111 --> 40:19.678
for violation
of Title 18 for fraud.

40:19.721 --> 40:22.202
- Wait, wait, what?
- What the hell?

40:22.245 --> 40:23.899
- Jessa Rinaldi,
you're under arrest

40:23.943 --> 40:26.293
for violation
of Title 18 for fraud.

40:26.336 --> 40:27.860
Any false statements
you make to the FBI

40:27.903 --> 40:30.776
are punishable for up
to five years in prison.

40:30.819 --> 40:32.734
- How could you do this, Will?

40:32.778 --> 40:34.562
How could you do this to me?

40:34.606 --> 40:36.782
- Wait, what? Was this you?

40:36.825 --> 40:43.832
<i>♪</i>

40:47.270 --> 40:49.969
- You called the FBI?
- I did.

40:50.012 --> 40:52.275
- But you told me--
- I told you to stand down.

40:52.319 --> 40:55.061
This is my responsibility,
not yours.

40:55.104 --> 40:59.805
Any and all fallout
lands on me, not you.

40:59.848 --> 41:03.286
- And believe me, Sharon,
there will be fallout.

41:03.330 --> 41:10.337
<i>♪</i>

41:21.783 --> 41:24.743
<i>[dramatic music]</i>

41:24.786 --> 41:31.793
<i>♪</i>

41:51.813 --> 41:54.816
[wolf howls]
